    title:'The Defect Impact Weight Table',
    subtitle:'The actual point values for every severity and location combination — the numbers you need to score a property',
    sections:[
      {
        heading:'Why the exact numbers matter',
        body:`Understanding that "LT in a unit deducts more than Low outside" is not enough to do your job. To project a score, advise a client on repair priority, or explain a REAC result, you need the actual point values.\n\nThe Defect Impact Weight table gives you a specific base deduction for every combination of severity level and inspectable area location. These base values are then divided by the number of units inspected to produce the actual score deduction at any given property.\n\nMastering this table is what separates a consultant who says "you should probably fix that" from one who says "fixing those three items moves your projected score from 58 to 67 — that's the difference between a fail and a pass." That second consultant charges more, gets rehired, and gets referrals.`
      },
      {
        heading:'The Defect Impact Weight table',
        body:`The following table shows the base point deduction for each combination of severity level and inspectable area. These are the values HUD uses in the NSPIRE scoring formula before dividing by units inspected.\n\nLIFE-THREATENING (LT):\n• Unit location: 60.0 base points\n• Inside location: 42.0 base points\n• Outside location: 24.0 base points\n\nSEVERE:\n• Unit location: 21.0 base points\n• Inside location: 14.7 base points\n• Outside location: 8.4 base points\n\nMODERATE:\n• Unit location: 7.5 base points\n• Inside location: 5.25 base points\n• Outside location: 3.0 base points\n\nLOW:\n• Unit location: 1.5 base points\n• Inside location: 1.05 base points\n• Outside location: 0.6 base points\n\nKey pattern to memorize: Each step up in severity roughly triples the deduction. Each step up in location (outside → inside → unit) adds roughly 40–75% more. A single LT unit deficiency (60 points) deducts the same as 8 Severe unit deficiencies (8 × 21 = 168... wait — it doesn't, which is why you need the table, not approximations).`
      },
      {
        heading:'How to calculate a single deficiency deduction',
        body:`The formula for any single deficiency is simple:\n\nPoint deduction = Base Defect Impact Weight ÷ Number of units inspected\n\nExamples:\n\nExample 1: One LT deficiency in a unit at a 10-unit property\n60.0 ÷ 10 = 6.0 points deducted from the score\n\nExample 2: One LT deficiency in a unit at a 50-unit property\n60.0 ÷ 50 = 1.2 points deducted from the score\n\nExample 3: One Severe deficiency in a unit at a 20-unit property\n21.0 ÷ 20 = 1.05 points deducted\n\nExample 4: One Moderate deficiency in a unit at a 20-unit property\n7.5 ÷ 20 = 0.375 points deducted\n\nExample 5: One Low deficiency outside at a 20-unit property\n0.6 ÷ 20 = 0.03 points deducted\n\nThis last example shows why outside Low items are essentially irrelevant at medium to large properties — a Low outside deficiency at a 20-unit building deducts 3 hundredths of a point. Your client could have 30 of them and lose less than 1 point. Don't let them spend money on these.`
      },
      {
        heading:'Calculating total score from multiple deficiencies',
        body:`To project a total score, follow these steps:\n\nStep 1: List every deficiency with its severity and location\nStep 2: Look up the base Defect Impact Weight for each\nStep 3: Apply the duplicate defects rule — if the same deficiency type appears multiple times in the same inspectable area, count it only once\nStep 4: Sum all base weights\nStep 5: Divide the total by the number of units inspected\nStep 6: Subtract from 100\nStep 7: Check the Unit Threshold — if unit deductions alone are 30+, it's a fail regardless of overall score\n\nWorked Example — 20-unit property:\nDeficiencies found:\n• 1 LT in unit (exposed wiring): 60.0\n• 2 Severe in units (GFCI missing, open ground) — two different types, both scored: 21.0 + 21.0 = 42.0\n• 3 Moderate in units (inoperable fixture, stove burner, water stain) — three different types: 7.5 + 7.5 + 7.5 = 22.5\n• 1 Severe inside (fire door propped open): 14.7\n• 2 Low outside (trip hazard, parking light): 0.6 + 0.6 = 1.2\n\nTotal base weight: 60.0 + 42.0 + 22.5 + 14.7 + 1.2 = 140.4\nDivide by 20 units: 140.4 ÷ 20 = 7.02 points deducted\nProjected score: 100 - 7.02 = 92.98 ≈ 93\n\nUnit deductions only: 60.0 + 42.0 + 22.5 = 124.5 ÷ 20 = 6.225 — well below the 30-point Unit Threshold\n\nResult: Projected PASS at approximately 93.`
      },
      {
        heading:'The Unit Threshold calculation',
        body:`The Unit Threshold is a separate calculation you must run every time, parallel to the overall score. Even if the overall score passes, the property fails if unit deductions alone equal 30+ points.\n\nUnit Threshold formula:\n(Sum of all unit-area base weights) ÷ (number of units inspected) ≥ 30 = FAIL\n\nWorked Example — 10-unit property at risk of Unit Threshold:\nUnit deficiencies:\n• 1 LT in unit: 60.0\n• 3 Severe in units (three different types): 21.0 × 3 = 63.0\n• 4 Moderate in units (four different types): 7.5 × 4 = 30.0\n\nUnit base weight total: 60.0 + 63.0 + 30.0 = 153.0\nUnit deduction: 153.0 ÷ 10 units = 15.3 points from units\nUnit Threshold: 15.3 is below 30 — threshold NOT triggered\n\nNow add Inside and Outside:\nInside: 1 Severe (14.7) + 2 Moderate (5.25 × 2 = 10.5) = 25.2\nOutside: 3 Low (0.6 × 3 = 1.8)\nTotal base: 153.0 + 25.2 + 1.8 = 180.0\nTotal deduction: 180.0 ÷ 10 = 18.0 points\nOverall score: 100 - 18.0 = 82 — PASS\n\nNow change the scenario: same property but with 5 LT in units instead of 1:\nUnit base: (60 × 5) + 63.0 + 30.0 = 393.0\nUnit deduction: 393.0 ÷ 10 = 39.3 points — UNIT THRESHOLD TRIGGERED\nOverall score may be high, but the property FAILS because unit deductions alone exceed 30.\n\nThis is the scenario that surprises property managers most. They assume a good overall score means a pass — but concentrated unit deficiencies can fail a property that looks fine on paper.`
      },
      {
        heading:'How sample size affects scoring — the REAC unit sample formula',
        body:`REAC does not inspect every unit. The number of units inspected in the sample directly affects every score calculation because all base weights are divided by this number.\n\nApproximate REAC sample sizes by property size:\n• 1–4 units: all units inspected\n• 5–9 units: approximately 4–5 units\n• 10–19 units: approximately 5–7 units\n• 20–39 units: approximately 8–12 units\n• 40–79 units: approximately 13–18 units\n• 80–199 units: approximately 19–28 units\n• 200+ units: approximately 28–35 units\n\nThe key insight: as property size grows, the sample size grows much more slowly. A 200-unit property might only have 30 units inspected. Each deficiency deduction is divided by 30, not 200 — making the per-deficiency impact smaller.\n\nFor small properties (under 20 units), a single LT deficiency can deduct 6–12 points from the score. For large properties (100+ units), the same deficiency might deduct less than 1 point.\n\nWhy this matters for your business:\n• Small property clients face disproportionate risk from individual deficiencies — your service is most urgently needed here\n• Large property clients have more statistical protection from individual deficiencies but have more units to walk — your service scales to portfolio size\n• For both, the goal is the same: bring every unit to a condition where it doesn't matter which ones get sampled`
      }
    ]
